<paragraph id="865162620682A7C2038A75348B916A5B" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="28D8F379107F8B46C20ED8615A3944F7" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops aslaki" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aslaki">
<emphasis id="0A4ACA333F6F585BE1DDD447ADD45042" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops aslaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. et sp. nov.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5FEC13ACD74E2EB92E65B35E2D3DD6C0" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="971D1676F16DD47AFE89FBC62FC970BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FC55E162CD04B939FC1D867D8EE5BFC1" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
From all other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="3F3F78230E32A71BEC0CB0672D0454D1" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Staphylininae">Staphylininae</taxonomicName>
the new genus can be recognized based on the following characters: antennomere 2 1.6
<normalizedToken id="77C2F556FC2A8614BF3A1DD59739490B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
wider than antennomere 3; antennomere 11 3
<normalizedToken id="2DF6095A81403EF5258A7345CBB297C8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than antennomere 10; penultimate segment of maxillary palpi large, covered in short setae, approximately 2
<normalizedToken id="5DA6AE6C11C6A8395F55965B80691319" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
the length of apical segment; apical segment of maxillary and labial palpi aciculate. Head with 'infraorbital 
<normalizedToken id="C1A4AF0BBC036EBE9415250CA262F140" originalValue="ridges’">ridges'</normalizedToken>
straight, extended to base of mandibles; postgenal ridge absent; frontoclypeal suture present; mesoventrite with transverse ridge present (incomplete medially); mesotrochanter and first mesotarsomere of males with black combs; tarsal formula 5-5-5; empodial setae long and parallel-sided; apical edge of sternites III to VI with randomly distributed acute projections; tergites VII and VIII with broader, foliose setae in addition to the usual acuminate, simple setae; apparent fusion of tergite X to lateral tergal sclerites in males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="80B7649CB7A341D9F6806C3FC259CB7B" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="3407CA4FCB2F3CE0D03267219BF0F6A9" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5487A81C423756893E071D10B2ADACEC" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
The differential diagnosis is based on the recovered phylogenetic position of 
<taxonomicName id="4D838A3C09FCDE314F06A2F21BB524B0" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7B3CC2E8357C9B3162D192E86478529F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its strong resemblance to the 
<taxonomicName id="8FD5E48D693836A0ED51A87B83A8B415" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="tribe" tribe="Amblyopinini">Amblyopinini</taxonomicName>
genus 
<taxonomicName id="E2376C3CC537F3B1226320007140F509" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Heterothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="01754A3AEC9D092D427B092FF8B3DD05" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Heterothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="CC3831FDFE650CDF484BB2072BC30A8A" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8909225A9590FF45AD5CE362D9BA28C1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="DA4774DAE395772469CEEE1D80CB5468" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atanygnathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atanygnathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5E961297C90C0C46699A8CB7F5DD720D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Atanygnathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Jacobson, 1909 (
<taxonomicName id="C32CB43E412C2842F442BECFD44EC942" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="tribe" tribe="Tanygnathinini">Tanygnathinini</taxonomicName>
) in the number of tarsal segments (5-4-4 in 
<taxonomicName id="6C3FFE06883236EA47851533F0478C47" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atanygnathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atanygnathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="953BDE3805495C4BFC33939C9DD10585" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Atanygnathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); short genae and normal shape of the apical labial and maxillary palpomere (extremely elongate and distinctly converging to apex in 
<taxonomicName id="EB70FA1B2CFAC08AC089D228879FAE9F" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atanygnathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atanygnathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E88C7B94C45D66C1D0161B55863A8613" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Atanygnathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); absence of dorsal setae on the apical tarsomere (present in 
<taxonomicName id="F88405861668061BCC7661DDCCECA0CE" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atanygnathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atanygnathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AF6E26AC772CAB934CE7E868390B4C63" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Atanygnathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It should be noted that some species of 
<taxonomicName id="802AA4570E801302F4E32150BA3636B0" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atanygnathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atanygnathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AE551E72F2D362686AFF20065D7E4748" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Atanygnathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have combs on the profemora (Adam Brunke, personal communication). 
<taxonomicName id="849A735A720C4E8271F2FF8C997E7F89" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AF1D129DBDFC20987A02C7ED7371703D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from species of 
<taxonomicName id="1F2C75539DF3E5F28EAC591D88A28DDE" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Holisus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holisus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8964A54172EE40FF1D2A47C8ECC9CF46" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Holisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Erichson, 1839 (
<taxonomicName id="D7487983F356425577815B9412653398" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="tribe" tribe="Hyptiomini">Hyptiomini</taxonomicName>
) in the pronotal hypomeron strongly inflexed, not visible in lateral view and without longitudinal middle carina (visible in lateral view and with middle carina in 
<taxonomicName id="49884628B0AF3BF9F458DBAC800611BC" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Holisus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holisus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BF6CA52D1097730F5C5878FF4299A88D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Holisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), presence of empodial setae (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="103757F8386EA0667E99C85D729C435C" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Holisus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holisus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1117F8ACC76BF276313B44D662044EF7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Holisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and general appearance and habitus (
<taxonomicName id="677D1D3BF75493B9F7BCC816ECC327EF" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Holisus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Holisus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="50F0E490C1DAF69A1250C37C467A7466" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Holisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctly dorso-ventrally flattened with coarse punctation). 
<taxonomicName id="0A15B8C9C39223F55587C0A3D584E0D5" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AB910E55FF06086DB1438B795734EC6D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the genus 
<taxonomicName id="1585386931A1AFF6FBE264FCAD8616C6" authorityName="Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Natalignathus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Natalignathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DEBF745AB22421F2CBE781CC666C6DD0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Natalignathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Solodovnikov, 2005, a hitherto unrecognized possible member of the same clade (see Discussion below) in the smaller body, short genae and much lesser elongate mouthparts, absence of dorsal setae on the apical tarsomere (present in 
<taxonomicName id="CE44DF8103FDC142AE597A9B474DE181" authorityName="Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Natalignathus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Natalignathus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="684BB453FE365F4B522E9B0D82DA8266" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Natalignathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and presence of the combs. 
<taxonomicName id="AC4204582A128C21D3243A6417450E26" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AA48599F7A9ED24AAB726CE3D675104D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="2A83435DBF2130B4B7C38A8930941BBA" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Heterothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="768CBD40DA7C638FF6683764E4C66829" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Heterothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other genera of 
<taxonomicName id="95A416779CEFE3452550374C8B4B2F85" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="tribe" tribe="Amblyopinini">Amblyopinini</taxonomicName>
in presence of the frontoclypeal suture; antennomere 3 distinctly smaller than antennomeres 2 and 4; mesosternum with transverse ridge present (incomplete medially); apical edge of sternites III to VI with randomly distributed acute projections; tergites VII and VIII with broader, foliose setae in addition to the usual acuminate, simple setae; and apparent fusion of tergite X to lateral sclerites in males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="18B3D10778C311D61E3A63DA49027C80" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="description">
<paragraph id="17C6A83410B29B077636F3128EBE61A8" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A0C729C24A4B968C3AF05F9FE6B59733" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
Habitus as in Fig. 
<figureCitation id="45FFF9CC4C740E0D7E2CB3B6B3421049" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Habitus of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372637" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">2</figureCitation>
. Body dark brown-black; antennae and legs yellowish. Measurements (all in mm): HW = 0.31; PL = 0.38; PW = 0.48; FB = 1.00; EW = 0.55; TL = 2.19.
</paragraph>
<caption id="614D26A936346BD4FB8657414DBA7284" doi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372637" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="90657CED31AAD97EFD66CE4F402FFC5F" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="73D5F460144A36C01435FE1844022980" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Figure 2.</emphasis>
Habitus of 
<taxonomicName id="C6EAEF1743A84022E15D629ACDBF1841" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops aslaki" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aslaki">
<emphasis id="C764DF87FB510FC6C655800ADD52C19B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops aslaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. et sp. nov. Scale bar: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6C3ABD3679948DE4056E7E0913E7FF1C" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="BD3EC67AA1EF1FA871B95F7AB35D8FA7" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Head.</emphasis>
Dorsal surface with weak transverse microsculpture. Neck indistinct; nuchal ridge absent dorsally, present laterally, extended as 'infraorbital 
<normalizedToken id="E4FDEE9EC3814E1E5D211F08AFF4ACEF" originalValue="ridge’">ridge'</normalizedToken>
towards base of mandibles. Frontoclypeal suture present. Frontoclypeal puncture present (
<bibRefCitation id="410F4D236DBADDB97DB7F510DF0CDD05" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" author="Brunke, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="166 - 197" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, AJ, Zyla, D, Yamamoto, S, Solodovnikov, A, 2019. Baltic amber Staphylinini (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae): a rove beetle fauna on the eve of our modern climate. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 187: 166 - 197, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" title="Baltic amber Staphylinini (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae): a rove beetle fauna on the eve of our modern climate." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" volume="187" year="2019">Brunke et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1). Anterior and posterior frontal punctures present (
<bibRefCitation id="243090C5CE9C77C914C130B07AF48C79" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" author="Brunke, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="166 - 197" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, AJ, Zyla, D, Yamamoto, S, Solodovnikov, A, 2019. Baltic amber Staphylinini (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae): a rove beetle fauna on the eve of our modern climate. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 187: 166 - 197, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" title="Baltic amber Staphylinini (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae): a rove beetle fauna on the eve of our modern climate." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" volume="187" year="2019">Brunke et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1). Single basal puncture present (
<bibRefCitation id="8AE6873863C16D31489E019D008EF10E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" author="Brunke, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="166 - 197" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, AJ, Zyla, D, Yamamoto, S, Solodovnikov, A, 2019. Baltic amber Staphylinini (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae): a rove beetle fauna on the eve of our modern climate. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 187: 166 - 197, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" title="Baltic amber Staphylinini (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylininae): a rove beetle fauna on the eve of our modern climate." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz021" volume="187" year="2019">Brunke et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1). Eyes occupying two thirds of the side of head; temples indistinct. Antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C8AE754A8A0C8A596C777A5247F49378" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3A</figureCitation>
) inserted close to margin of eye. Antennomeres 1 to 3 setiferous; 4 to 11 setiferous and with tomentose pubescence. Antennomere 2 1.6
<normalizedToken id="18D9355C8861F510EB0EDF901A29B3AC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
the width of antennomere 3; antennomere 3 half the size of antennomere 2; antennomere 11 elongate, three times as long as antennomere 10. Gula widest in anterior half; gular sutures separated along entire length; postgenal ridge absent. Maxillary palpi four-segmented (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C13D2E548C9A8E73403A601E6F071394" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3B</figureCitation>
; apical segment acicular, about a third of the length of the penultimate palpomere; penultimate segment widest at middle; covered with setae. Labial palpi three-segmented (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="77102138F987D9F3594C9895F54D0CB9" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3C</figureCitation>
); apical segmented acicular. Labrum transverse, complete, without emargination. Mandibles simple, crossing in resting position, without large teeth.
</paragraph>
<caption id="5D721F19A937F1DFC1E781B454B6C677" doi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="C1D12DD29022DFE572BBD071A782A35D" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="FD1E336A9E636D9B4AF6A022EF035245" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Figure 3.</emphasis>
Morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="6B40E769AA8CC4BB18496007E2E4EC4F" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops aslaki" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aslaki">
<emphasis id="8F6411AFA1A26A8396813C7C2A348D5F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops aslaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. et sp. nov. 
<emphasis id="3E12F957E7DE22CA4A0586F5BBF0EE9C" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">A</emphasis>
antennae 
<emphasis id="1DA06EF580A07F43CF1107E5ECB173D9" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">B</emphasis>
maxillary palpi 
<emphasis id="0633FD2F00E29BA308A17803E3436DA9" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">C</emphasis>
labial palpi 
<emphasis id="4BA05FE7032BC87D4BCD7C51C5C0B94A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D</emphasis>
meso- and metathorax 
<emphasis id="77050069D93F65D31078F8F22F5CA872" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">E</emphasis>
mesothorax 
<emphasis id="AB748F7FB8D73770156D0EE68604C498" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">F</emphasis>
protergal gland 
<emphasis id="DD6BD0686648C6D68C9890BE82E8306D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">G</emphasis>
tergite II 
<emphasis id="B33C4D30850840D0259B746762EFAC34" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">H</emphasis>
sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="C6CA8224024F33EA9333B16404796CE4" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="EB314B5BA23534647648CC0FCFEE493B" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Prothorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum widest in posterior third. Dorsal surface with weak transverse microsculpture and two pairs of punctures in dorsal series (one puncture near posterior margin and one distad of that); hypomeron strongly inflexed (not visible in lateral view). Basisternum with weak longitudinal ridge in posterior half, without punctures or setae. Post-coxal process absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3045D89116F03658770BDAFC4E9ED73C" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
Scutellum with anterior transverse ridge only, impunctate, glabrous. Elytra widest posteriorly. Hind wings fully developed, posterior edge with fringe of setae; veins CuA and MP4 fused; vein MP3 present. Mesoventrite (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="413233C5A391EB287F0AC9D48000271C" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3D</figureCitation>
) with five large punctures medially (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="18222863C4FA6438D6223C6FF54346EA" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3D</figureCitation>
; Pu), with rounded ventral process and with transverse ridge, incomplete medially (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="99A9DAF3C5AEBB86B2694033BA884155" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9794B8CD9B537AA6CE1863E3C485E8C3" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="68FA508206F31500041107FEA5F5D794" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Protergal glands elongate, fringed by setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DA4B9AF03F2684857496CA0A137094BD" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3F</figureCitation>
). Tergites with anterior transverse carina only. Tergite II as in Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0B0FD7E268CDBE516AB4FD1B28B8B39D" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3G</figureCitation>
. Sternite III with evenly curved transverse carina, slightly projected medially. Tergite VII with white fringe along posterior edge. Apical edge of sternites III to VI with randomly distributed acute projections (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="90644A82763EC0C15E586469E539CD46" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A antennae B maxillary palpi C labial palpi D meso- and metathorax E mesothorax F protergal gland G tergite II H sternite III (apical edge). LP, Labial palpomere; MP, Maxillary palpomere; Pu, punctures; TR, Transverse ridge." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372638" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3H</figureCitation>
). Tergites VII and VIII with broader, foliose setae in addition to the usual acuminate, simple setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="934ABB53A119C171D1C41F446046CFEE" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A tergite VII B tergite VII C abdominal apex (tergites VII and VIII) D empodium of mesotarsi E empodium of metatarsi F mesotarsi (male) G mesotrochanter (male) H mesoleg (male). ES, Empodial setae; FS, Foliose setae; MS, Mesotarsomere; MSTr, Mesotrochanter; SS, Simple setae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">4A-C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="344F750DC3E7FBA63141C341BAAEFD14" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="89046BC5ED50F93E224C792B6BFF9207" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Legs.</emphasis>
Tarsal formula 5-5-5. Both sexes with protarsomeres 1 to 4 transverse. All tarsal empodia with long, parallel-sided setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1638C2942D6649F7E984749D92D8CDB4" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A tergite VII B tergite VII C abdominal apex (tergites VII and VIII) D empodium of mesotarsi E empodium of metatarsi F mesotarsi (male) G mesotrochanter (male) H mesoleg (male). ES, Empodial setae; FS, Foliose setae; MS, Mesotarsomere; MSTr, Mesotrochanter; SS, Simple setae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">4D, E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A26ABA26ECBBE3DC597CDE1874FACAC" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="D492F41BD25BBFF02C466E7D01278589" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Male.</emphasis>
Protarsomeres 1 to 4 with white adhesive setae ventrally. First mesotarsomere with black comb comprising 11-14 articles (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E08F292501650632B136A1AB8541093B" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A tergite VII B tergite VII C abdominal apex (tergites VII and VIII) D empodium of mesotarsi E empodium of metatarsi F mesotarsi (male) G mesotrochanter (male) H mesoleg (male). ES, Empodial setae; FS, Foliose setae; MS, Mesotarsomere; MSTr, Mesotrochanter; SS, Simple setae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">4F, H</figureCitation>
). Mesotrochanter with black comb comprising 7-11 articles (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="18C2804E6B0542BAC00B1B20368AD21C" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A tergite VII B tergite VII C abdominal apex (tergites VII and VIII) D empodium of mesotarsi E empodium of metatarsi F mesotarsi (male) G mesotrochanter (male) H mesoleg (male). ES, Empodial setae; FS, Foliose setae; MS, Mesotarsomere; MSTr, Mesotrochanter; SS, Simple setae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">4G, H</figureCitation>
). The number of articles within each comb varies between individuals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="37039CF4222B05CD5786CBB5E35193E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="8D78266CBEB01A36AD57350C418DD922" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Female.</emphasis>
Protarsomeres 1 to 4 only with usual setae ventrally, white adhesive setae absent. No combs.
</paragraph>
<caption id="9A368683EDEDCC6828F1A10E2D47E0F9" doi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
