</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E3B8150F7D2759C81C0B22843FC2B961" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9D9B2C1615A41CFC771A1670465E4A13" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61146D8FED9C1A69506DF35E7CC7240F" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Based on the specimens studied here, the new genus is restricted to the lowland areas of the Amazonian basin of Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DF26998BAA4A64F93A71B3BF67BBA55C" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="bionomics">
<paragraph id="532BC624473BD574BB72A05DCFC57EB8" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Bionomics.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB04BC149BAE5CA62B3D71A13C9F71B7" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Based on the available label data, the genus occurs in forested areas (100-420 m elevation) and has so far only been collected by flight intercept traps.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="74A2318809290105117CD0CE71F2FFA1" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E5372CF9D38D09288D4D2485FEB414FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="38C296EBB705F3861CD6E53A08BC90E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
The genus name is a combination of 
<normalizedToken id="A514A66D174A58084B9C1F1950C3F2C0" originalValue="‘Amazon’">'Amazon'</normalizedToken>
and the genus name 
<taxonomicName id="C3776519724F99DADE706AB0805E1B2D" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Heterothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3ACB26E9AC9DA36371D3EF6B5E6B82A9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Heterothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which the new genus strongly resembles superficially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1AAF8D2A05DB513C9A463AE5F4B5FB24" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="269C6579707555DCC0BFA216ACCDA192" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B220D1CCEC4139D80060262DC163471B" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
The new genus is certainly morphologically distinct among other members of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="278DE57866E9F32C061E493E3C6C097B" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Staphylininae">Staphylininae</taxonomicName>
and family 
<taxonomicName id="1FD7EA36AD16BE2C5D79C000B29B275A" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Staphylinidae</taxonomicName>
. Noteworthy is the secondary sexual dimorphism exhibited by 
<taxonomicName id="2BC102B32714F67508F97919EBD9594E" authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="42D81D4BCB7F4E7C7F55073546DE8311" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In males, the mesotrochanter and first mesotarsomere have distinct black combs which are completely lacking in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="92AB4F3D9D05B5DA5D631EF3A80DD7D4" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A tergite VII B tergite VII C abdominal apex (tergites VII and VIII) D empodium of mesotarsi E empodium of metatarsi F mesotarsi (male) G mesotrochanter (male) H mesoleg (male). ES, Empodial setae; FS, Foliose setae; MS, Mesotarsomere; MSTr, Mesotrochanter; SS, Simple setae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">4F, G, H</figureCitation>
). The function, if any, of the combs remains unknown but very similar combs are commonly found within 
<taxonomicName id="4D169F198F21E1182B80188C54E8F049" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="tribe" tribe="Amblyopinini">Amblyopinini</taxonomicName>
, e.g., recently illustrated for 
<taxonomicName id="6A5428BE6684886277F956F209C61D4C" authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1883" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Myotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myotyphlus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C644F1A1302BAF3D64BA8F1F32392359" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fauvel, 1883 (
<bibRefCitation id="5511DD546EA1A2C16ED3877982079690" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/aen.12233" author="Solodovnikov, A" journalOrPublisher="Austral Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="311 - 321" refId="B12" refString="Solodovnikov, A, Jenkins Shaw, J, 2017. The remarkable Australian rove beetle genus Myotyphlus: its cryptic diversity and significance for exploring mutualism among insects and mammals (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Austral Entomology 56: 311 - 321, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/aen.12233" title="The remarkable Australian rove beetle genus Myotyphlus: its cryptic diversity and significance for exploring mutualism among insects and mammals (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/aen.12233" volume="56" year="2017">Solodovnikov and Jenkins Shaw 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
